South Korea Stocks: Kia Motors, LG Display, Samsung, S-Oil

-- B y   S a e r o m i   S h i n
-- 
2011-07-22T06:39:03Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-07-22/south-korea-stocks-kia-motors-lg-display-samsung-s-oil.html
Shares of the following companies
had unusual moves in South Korea trading. Stock symbols are in
parentheses and prices are as of the 3 p.m. close in Seoul.  The  Kospi Index (KOSPI)  rose 26.19, or 1.2 percent, to 2,171.23,
the steepest increase since June 29. The gauge added 1.2 percent
this week.  Refiners: SK Innovation Co. (096770 KS) climbed 2.7 percent
to 213,000 won.  S-Oil Corp. (010950)  (010950 KS) rallied 7 percent to
153,500 won, the largest jump since April 21. Crude oil advanced
in  New York , heading for a fourth week of gains, as signs  Europe 
and the U.S. will contain their debt crises eased speculation
that demand for raw materials may falter.  Kia Motors Corp. (000270)  (000270 KS), an affiliate of Hyundai Motor
Co., advanced 3.1 percent to 77,300 won, the highest close since
May 2. The company and its workers tentatively agreed on 2011
salary increases, according to a statement by the South Korean
automaker.  LG Display Co. (034220 KS), the world’s second-largest
maker of liquid-crystal displays, lost 2.6 percent to 29,450
won, the biggest drop since July 12. The company reported a 96
percent drop in second-quarter profit amid a slump in panel
demand. LG Display had a net income of 21.3 billion won ($20
million) in the three months ended in June compared with a
profit of 554.8 billion won a year earlier, according to a
statement.  Samsung Engineering Co. (028050 KS),  South Korea ’s largest
engineering company, gained 2.2 percent to 280,500 won, a record
close. The company had its share-price estimate raised to
350,000 won from 300,000 won at Daewoo Securities Co., which
cited a higher earnings outlook, according to a report today.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Saeromi Shin in Seoul at 
